# Linux Latency Diagnostics and Scheduler Profiler

Linux-first diagnostics toolkit for tracking syscall latency, scheduler delays, interrupt behavior, and cross-release performance regressions in latency-sensitive services.

## Why this project exists

Tail latency problems are rarely obvious from CPU and memory dashboards alone. This repository focuses on the system-level signals that usually explain the ugly cases: runnable queue buildup, interrupt storms, syscall tail growth, CPU hot spots, and scheduler delays that only show up under load. The goal is to make release-to-release comparison practical instead of turning every investigation into an ad hoc shell session.

The implementation follows the scope implied by the source README: Python for offline analysis, Bash for host-side collection, `perf` and tracing-oriented workflows for Linux visibility, Grafana-ready outputs for dashboards, and an eBPF-style capture hook for environments that use `bpftrace` or similar tooling.

## What is included

- Python CLI for capture, summary, regression comparison, and report generation
- Host collection wrappers for `perf`, `ftrace`, and optional `bpftrace`
- Offline comparison workflow that flags latency regressions across releases
- CPU hot-spot ranking and syscall-tail analysis
- Scheduler-delay breakdowns by process name
- Static HTML report generation for incident review and handoff
- Grafana dashboard JSON stub for teams that export metrics into a dashboard system
- Sample captures and a reproducible demo workflow
- Tests, Docker support for analysis-only usage, and CI

